<emphasis id="18AD837AFC46FFD0F181A8413566FAE3" bold="true" box="[189,310,1297,1323]" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2A665F68FC46FFD1F181A81035D2FE31" blockId="58.[189,1399,1344,2004]" lastBlockId="59.[189,1399,267,505]" lastPageId="59" lastPageNumber="60" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">
Fore wing length (15) 
<quantity id="ED21F28DFC46FFD0F0EBA810360EFA92" box="[471,606,1344,1370]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.8" metricValueMax="1.9" metricValueMin="1.7" pageId="58" pageNumber="59" unit="mm" value="18.0" valueMax="19.0" valueMin="17.0">17–19 mm</quantity>
. Antenna with 48–55 flagellomeres. First flagellomere 4.0 times as long as wide. Second flagellomere about 2.0 times as long as wide. Central flagellomeres about 1.5–1.6 times as long as wide. Apical flagellomeres approximately 1.5 times as long as wide. Flagellomeres in females, less so in males, with rather long prominent pilosity. Length of pilosity about 0.5 width of flagellomere (
<figureCitation id="B2E243EDFC46FFD0F378A89C36F2FA2F" box="[580,674,1484,1511]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="16.[189,232,1605,1631]" captionTargetBox="[285,1312,292,1544]" captionTargetId="figure@16.[261,1325,266,1568]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="Fig. 8. A–C.Apical flagellomeres in female. A. Ophion parvulusKriechbaumer, 1879. B. O. paraparvulus Johansson sp. nov., paratype, ♀ (NHRS-HEVA000008696). C. O. tenuicornis Johansson sp. nov., paratype, ♀ (NHRS-HEVA000008743). D–F. Apical flagellomeres in female (pilosity removed). D. O. ellenae Johansson sp. nov., paratype, ♀ (NHRS-HEVA000008655). E. O. arenarius Johansson sp. nov., paratype, ♀ (NHRS-HEVA000008606). F. O. inclinans Johansson sp. nov., holotype, ♀ (NHRS-HEVA000008667). G–H. Apical hind tarsal segments dorsal view in female. G. O. parvulus. H. O. costatus Ratzeburg, 1848. I–J. Generalized punctation below antennal sockets in anterior view. I. O. confusus Johansson sp. nov., holotype, ♀ (NHRS-HEVA000008637). J. O. mocsaryi Brauns, 1889. K–L. Posterior segments of female metasoma lateral view. K. O. areolaris Brauns, 1889. L. O. ocellaris Ulbricht, 1926. M. Central flagellomeres in female of O. brevicornis Morley, 1915. N–O. Basal flagellomeres. N. O. confusus Johansson sp. nov., holotype, ♀ (NHRS-HEVA000008637). O. O. mocsaryi." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3476420" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3476420/files/figure.png" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Fig. 8B</figureCitation>
). Head narrowed behind eyes, in lateral view temple 0.4–0.5 as long as compound eye, more buccate in males, 0.6–0.7 times as wide as compound eye. Lateral ocellus touching compound eye. In female lateral ocelli quite large, the distance between lateral ocelli about 0.4 times the diameter of ocellus. Malar space about 0.1 times as long as mandibular base in female and about 0.2–0.3 times in males. Mandibular gape right-angled, with internal angles. Wing membrane weakly yellowish. Ramellus distinct, reaching 0.2–0.3 the width of discosubmarginal cell. Radius evenly curved (as in 
<figureCitation id="B2E243EDFC46FFD0F328ABF036D2F972" box="[532,642,1696,1722]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="22.[189,232,1802,1828]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,673,1763]" captionTargetId="figure@22.[189,1398,673,1763]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="Fig.13.A.Right forewingOphiontenuicornisJohanssonsp.nov.,paratype,♀(NHRS-HEVA000008743), the evenly curved radius arrowed. B. Pterostigma O. autumnalis Johansson sp. nov., holotype, ♀ (NHRS-HEVA000008620). C. Right fore wing O. inclinans Johansson sp. nov., holotype, ♀ (NHRS- HEVA000008667), the sinous radius arrowed. D. Pterostigma O. kevoensis Jussila, 1965. E–F. Hind wing nervellus, interception of discoidella arrowed. E. O. brocki Johansson sp. nov., paratype, ♀ (NHRS- HEVA000008633). F. O. splendens Johansson sp. nov., paratype, ♀ (NHRS-HEVA000008708)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3476432" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3476432/files/figure.png" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Fig. 13A</figureCitation>
). Mesopleuron polished or sometimes weakly shagreened with quite weak punctures, interstices between punctures about equal or slightly larger than their diameter. Epicnemial carina, in antero-ventral view, with pleurosternal angles obviously anterior to sternal angles. Pleurosternal angles rounded, strongly obtuse. Scutellum with lateral carinae only indicated basally (as in 
<figureCitation id="B2E243EDFC46FFD0F05DAA7C3590F88F" box="[353,448,1836,1863]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="14.[189,232,1841,1867]" captionTargetBox="[273,1272,270,1727]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[189,1398,270,1796]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Fig. 6. A–D. Scutellum, dorsal view. A. Ophion luteus (Linnaeus, 1758). B. O. areolaris Brauns, 1889. C. O. inclinans Johansson sp. nov., holotype, ♀ (NHRS-HEVA000008667). D. O. dispar Brauns, 1895. E–H. Firsttergite, lateral view.E. O.inclinansJohanssonsp.nov.,holotype,♀ (NHRS-HEVA000008667). F. O. dispar. G. O. artemisiae Boie, 1855. H. O. luteus. I–J. Shape of male parameres, lateral view. I. Ophion sp. cf. pseudocostatus Meyer, 1935. J. O. artemisiae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3476414" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3476414/files/figure.png" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Fig. 6A</figureCitation>
). Propodeum with very weak rugose structure, shiny with anterior and posterior transverse carina strongly raised in female (
<figureCitation id="B2E243EDFC46FFD0F3EBAA00371AF8A2" box="[727,842,1872,1898]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="18.[189,232,1739,1765]" captionTargetBox="[305,1281,298,1666]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[263,1325,265,1697]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="Fig. 10. Generalized carination of propodeum in females, posterodorsal view. A. Ophion luteus (Linnaeus, 1758)/O. scutellaris Thomson, 1888/O. obscuratus Fabricius, 1792. B. O. costatus Ratzeburg, 1848. C. O. brocki Johansson sp. nov., paratype, ♀ (NHRS-HEVA000008633). D. O. confusus Johansson sp. nov., holotype, ♀ (NHRS-HEVA000008637). E. O. crassicornis Brock, 1982. F. O. artemisiae Boie, 1855. G. O. ellenae Johansson sp. nov., paratype, ♀ (NHRS-HEVA000008655). H. O. perkinsi Brock, 1982. I. O. ocellaris Ulbricht, 1926. J. O. areolaris Brauns, 1889. K. O. dispar Brauns, 1895. L. O. tenuicornis Johansson sp. nov., paratype, ♀ (NHRS-HEVA000008743). M. O. longigena Thomson, 1888. N. O. brevicornis Morley, 1915. O. O. forticornis Morley, 1915." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3476424" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3476424/files/figure.png" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">Figs 10B</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="B2E243EDFC46FFD0F265AA003728F8A2" box="[857,888,1872,1898]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="117.[189,232,1983,2009]" captionTargetBox="[317,1270,1557,1943]" captionTargetId="figure@117.[317,1270,1557,1943]" captionTargetPageId="117" captionText="Fig. 47. Propodeum of females, posterodorsal view. A‒B. Ophion costatus Ratzeburg, 1848." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3476510" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3476510/files/figure.png" pageId="58" pageNumber="59">47</figureCitation>
A–B). Anterior transverse carina in males often weak or absent laterally. Petiolar carinae usually strong. Longitudinal carinae delimiting area superomedia in large specimens rather strong, in smaller specimens frequently weak or absent, but normally clearly indicated at the junction with the posterior transverse carina. Propodeum centrally, between anterior and posterior transverse carina, usually with a distinct longitudinal fold in both males and females (
<figureCitation id="B2E243EDFC47FFD1F05CAC7E3584FE81" box="[352,468,302,329]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="18.[189,232,1739,1765]" captionTargetBox="[305,1281,298,1666]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[263,1325,265,1697]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="Fig. 10. Generalized carination of propodeum in females, posterodorsal view. A. Ophion luteus (Linnaeus, 1758)/O. scutellaris Thomson, 1888/O. obscuratus Fabricius, 1792. B. O. costatus Ratzeburg, 1848. C. O. brocki Johansson sp. nov., paratype, ♀ (NHRS-HEVA000008633). D. O. confusus Johansson sp. nov., holotype, ♀ (NHRS-HEVA000008637). E. O. crassicornis Brock, 1982. F. O. artemisiae Boie, 1855. G. O. ellenae Johansson sp. nov., paratype, ♀ (NHRS-HEVA000008655). H. O. perkinsi Brock, 1982. I. O. ocellaris Ulbricht, 1926. J. O. areolaris Brauns, 1889. K. O. dispar Brauns, 1895. L. O. tenuicornis Johansson sp. nov., paratype, ♀ (NHRS-HEVA000008743). M. O. longigena Thomson, 1888. N. O. brevicornis Morley, 1915. O. O. forticornis Morley, 1915." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3476424" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3476424/files/figure.png" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Figs 10B</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="B2E243EDFC47FFD1F0DEAC7F364AFE81" box="[482,538,303,329]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="117.[189,232,1983,2009]" captionTargetBox="[317,1270,1557,1943]" captionTargetId="figure@117.[317,1270,1557,1943]" captionTargetPageId="117" captionText="Fig. 47. Propodeum of females, posterodorsal view. A‒B. Ophion costatus Ratzeburg, 1848." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3476510" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3476510/files/figure.png" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">47A</figureCitation>
). Hind trochantellus shorter than wide in dorsal view. Legs, especially in females, normally quite stout with hind femur about 6.0 times as long as wide. Hind tarsus stout, fourth segment about 2 times as long as wide; fifth segment slightly longer than fourth (
<figureCitation id="B2E243EDFC47FFD1F5EFAC253162FE47" box="[1235,1330,373,399]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="16.[189,232,1605,1631]" captionTargetBox="[285,1312,292,1544]" captionTargetId="figure@16.[261,1325,266,1568]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="Fig. 8. A–C.Apical flagellomeres in female. A. Ophion parvulusKriechbaumer, 1879. B. O. paraparvulus Johansson sp. nov., paratype, ♀ (NHRS-HEVA000008696). C. O. tenuicornis Johansson sp. nov., paratype, ♀ (NHRS-HEVA000008743). D–F. Apical flagellomeres in female (pilosity removed). D. O. ellenae Johansson sp. nov., paratype, ♀ (NHRS-HEVA000008655). E. O. arenarius Johansson sp. nov., paratype, ♀ (NHRS-HEVA000008606). F. O. inclinans Johansson sp. nov., holotype, ♀ (NHRS-HEVA000008667). G–H. Apical hind tarsal segments dorsal view in female. G. O. parvulus. H. O. costatus Ratzeburg, 1848. I–J. Generalized punctation below antennal sockets in anterior view. I. O. confusus Johansson sp. nov., holotype, ♀ (NHRS-HEVA000008637). J. O. mocsaryi Brauns, 1889. K–L. Posterior segments of female metasoma lateral view. K. O. areolaris Brauns, 1889. L. O. ocellaris Ulbricht, 1926. M. Central flagellomeres in female of O. brevicornis Morley, 1915. N–O. Basal flagellomeres. N. O. confusus Johansson sp. nov., holotype, ♀ (NHRS-HEVA000008637). O. O. mocsaryi." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3476420" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3476420/files/figure.png" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Fig. 8H</figureCitation>
), mid tarsus with fourth segment stout 0.6 times as long as fifth segment. Sclerotised part of first sternite ending slightly posterior to spiracle (as in 
<figureCitation id="B2E243EDFC47FFD1F3FFACEB375BFE1E" box="[707,779,443,470]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="14.[189,232,1841,1867]" captionTargetBox="[273,1272,270,1727]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[189,1398,270,1796]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="Fig. 6. A–D. Scutellum, dorsal view. A. Ophion luteus (Linnaeus, 1758). B. O. areolaris Brauns, 1889. C. O. inclinans Johansson sp. nov., holotype, ♀ (NHRS-HEVA000008667). D. O. dispar Brauns, 1895. E–H. Firsttergite, lateral view.E. O.inclinansJohanssonsp.nov.,holotype,♀ (NHRS-HEVA000008667). F. O. dispar. G. O. artemisiae Boie, 1855. H. O. luteus. I–J. Shape of male parameres, lateral view. I. Ophion sp. cf. pseudocostatus Meyer, 1935. J. O. artemisiae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3476414" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3476414/files/figure.png" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
G–H). Inner spur of hind tibia as long as 0.4 times hind metatarsus.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2A665F68FC47FFD1F181AF703544FDF2" blockId="59.[189,276,544,570]" box="[189,276,544,570]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
<heading id="712EE804FC47FFD1F181AF703544FDF2" bold="true" box="[189,276,544,570]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" reason="3">
<emphasis id="18AD837AFC47FFD1F181AF703544FDF2" bold="true" box="[189,276,544,570]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Colour</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2A665F68FC47FFD1F181AF1E35E2FD3D" blockId="59.[189,1399,590,757]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Body testaceous, frequently with distinct brownish patches on mesosternum, mesopleuron, propodeum and three stripes on mesoscutum. Mandibular teeth black. Inner and outer eye margins yellowish. First tergite often distinctly paler anterior to spiracle. Antennae bright orange. Ovipositor sheath often infuscate, slightly contrasting with posterior metasomal segments, in specimens with infuscate markings frequently brownish.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2A665F68FC47FFD1F181AE4D3536FCFF" blockId="59.[189,358,797,823]" box="[189,358,797,823]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
<heading id="712EE804FC47FFD1F181AE4D3536FCFF" bold="true" box="[189,358,797,823]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" reason="3">
<emphasis id="18AD837AFC47FFD1F181AE4D3536FCFF" bold="true" box="[189,358,797,823]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">DNA barcode</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2A665F68FC47FFD1F181AE1B3565FC64" blockId="59.[189,1399,843,940]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
The DNA barcode sequences of nine Swedish specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="EDD924EBFC47FFD1F241AE1B306CFCAD" authorityName="Ratzeburg" authorityYear="1848" box="[893,1084,843,869]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Ophion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="costatus">
<emphasis id="18AD837AFC47FFD1F241AE1B306CFCAD" box="[893,1084,843,869]" italics="true" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Ophion costatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are available at the BOLD systems database (www.boldsystems.org, BIN. BOLD: ADG0653. Specimen codes: STI-NJBC: 35, 38, 235–241).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="62C30CE3FC47FFD1F181AE8336EDFB4D" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="2A665F68FC47FFD1F181AE833570FC25" blockId="59.[189,288,979,1005]" box="[189,288,979,1005]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
<heading id="712EE804FC47FFD1F181AE833570FC25" bold="true" box="[189,288,979,1005]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" reason="3">
<emphasis id="18AD837AFC47FFD1F181AE833570FC25" bold="true" box="[189,288,979,1005]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Ecology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2A665F68FC47FFD1F181A95236EDFB4D" blockId="59.[189,1398,1026,1158]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
The species occurs primarily in forest landscapes and is active during August–October. The known hosts are 
<taxonomicName id="EDD924EBFC47FFD1F1D6A9753609FBF7" authority="Ochsenheimer, 1816" authorityName="Ochsenheimer" authorityYear="1816" box="[234,601,1061,1087]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Acronicta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="18AD837AFC47FFD1F1D6A975350DFBF7" box="[234,349,1061,1087]" italics="true" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Acronicta</emphasis>
Ochsenheimer, 1816
</taxonomicName>
species. 
<taxonomicName id="EDD924EBFC47FFD1F3FBA97537D9FBF7" authorityName="Ratzeburg" authorityYear="1848" box="[711,905,1061,1087]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Ophion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="costatus">
<emphasis id="18AD837AFC47FFD1F3FBA97537D9FBF7" box="[711,905,1061,1087]" italics="true" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Ophion costatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been reared from 
<taxonomicName id="EDD924EBFC47FFD1F5ABA97535D6FBAB" authority="(Linnaeus, 1758)" authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Acronicta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leporina">
<emphasis id="18AD837AFC47FFD1F5ABA9753126FBF7" box="[1175,1398,1061,1087]" italics="true" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Acronicta leporina</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="4E482299FC47FFD1F1F9A918352EFBAB" author="Linnaeus" box="[197,382,1096,1123]" firstAuthor="Linnaeus" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" refId="ref65400" refString="Linnaeus C. von 1758. Systema naturae per regna tria naturae, secundum classes, ordines, genera, species cum characteribus, differentiis, synonymis locis. Tomus I. Editio decima, reformata. Laurentii Salvii, Stockholm [Holmiae]. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 542" type="book" year="1758">Linnaeus, 1758</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
and the original description refers to a rearing from 
<taxonomicName id="EDD924EBFC47FFD1F2C4A9193166FBAB" authority="(Linnaeus, 1758)" authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[1016,1334,1096,1123]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Acronicta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aceris">
<emphasis id="18AD837AFC47FFD1F2C4A9193031FBAA" box="[1016,1121,1097,1123]" italics="true" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">A. aceris</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="4E482299FC47FFD1F54DA918317CFBAB" author="Linnaeus" box="[1137,1324,1096,1123]" firstAuthor="Linnaeus" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" refId="ref65400" refString="Linnaeus C. von 1758. Systema naturae per regna tria naturae, secundum classes, ordines, genera, species cum characteribus, differentiis, synonymis locis. Tomus I. Editio decima, reformata. Laurentii Salvii, Stockholm [Holmiae]. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 542" type="book" year="1758">Linnaeus, 1758</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
, both of which have very hairy final instar larvae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="62C30CE3FC47FFD1F181A9FD37AAFB3D" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="2A665F68FC47FFD1F181A9FD358DFB0F" blockId="59.[189,477,1197,1223]" box="[189,477,1197,1223]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
<heading id="712EE804FC47FFD1F181A9FD358DFB0F" bold="true" box="[189,477,1197,1223]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" reason="3">
<emphasis id="18AD837AFC47FFD1F181A9FD358DFB0F" bold="true" box="[189,477,1197,1223]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
Distribution in 
<collectingCountry id="52CE1FF8FC47FFD1F041A9FD358DFB0F" box="[381,477,1197,1223]" name="Sweden" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Sweden</collectingCountry>
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2A665F68FC47FFD1F181A98B37AAFB3D" blockId="59.[189,1018,1243,1270]" box="[189,1018,1243,1270]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
A common species in Southern and Central 
<collectingCountry id="52CE1FF8FC47FFD1F3FDA98B3771FB3D" box="[705,801,1243,1269]" name="Sweden" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Sweden</collectingCountry>
, rarer in the north.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="62C30CE3FC47FFD1F181A84D3661F994" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="2A665F68FC47FFD1F181A84D357FFAFF" blockId="59.[189,303,1309,1335]" box="[189,303,1309,1335]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
<heading id="712EE804FC47FFD1F181A84D357FFAFF" bold="true" box="[189,303,1309,1335]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" reason="3">
<emphasis id="18AD837AFC47FFD1F181A84D357FFAFF" bold="true" box="[189,303,1309,1335]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2A665F68FC47FFD1F181A81B3661F994" blockId="59.[189,1399,1355,1628]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">
The 
<typeStatus id="F562E1CAFC47FFD1F1C4A81C357BFAAE" box="[248,299,1356,1382]" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">type</typeStatus>
material of 
<taxonomicName id="EDD924EBFC47FFD1F0F7A81B36C1FAAD" authorityName="Ratzeburg" authorityYear="1848" box="[459,657,1355,1381]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Ophion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="costatus">
<emphasis id="18AD837AFC47FFD1F0F7A81B36C1FAAD" box="[459,657,1355,1381]" italics="true" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Ophion costatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is lost and the species has historically been the subject of numerous misinterpretations. This study shows that the name applies to one of the species in an aggregate previously treated under the name 
<taxonomicName id="EDD924EBFC47FFD1F3D9A8C237E1FA64" authorityName="Kriechbaumer" authorityYear="1879" box="[741,945,1426,1452]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Ophion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="parvulus">
<emphasis id="18AD837AFC47FFD1F3D9A8C237E1FA64" box="[741,945,1426,1452]" italics="true" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Ophion parvulus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see Discussion). 
<taxonomicName id="EDD924EBFC47FFD1F5A8A8C23108FA64" authorityName="Ratzeburg" authorityYear="1848" box="[1172,1368,1426,1452]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Ophion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="costatus">
<emphasis id="18AD837AFC47FFD1F5A8A8C23108FA64" box="[1172,1368,1426,1452]" italics="true" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Ophion costatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinguished from the other species in the aggregate currently known from 
<collectingCountry id="52CE1FF8FC47FFD1F55AA8E53094FA07" box="[1126,1220,1461,1487]" name="Sweden" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Sweden</collectingCountry>
on the stouter tarsal segments in the female, the usually typical carination of the propodeum and the generally larger size. The flagellomeres have approximately the same shape as in 
<taxonomicName id="EDD924EBFC47FFD1F2E7A8AB30F5F9DD" authorityName="Kriechbaumer" authorityYear="1879" box="[987,1189,1531,1557]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Ophion" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="59" pageNumber="60" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="parvulus">
<emphasis id="18AD837AFC47FFD1F2E7A8AB30F5F9DD" box="[987,1189,1531,1557]" italics="true" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Ophion parvulus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but usually have slightly longer pilosity. The barcoded specimens (
<figureCitation id="B2E243EDFC47FFD1F220AB4E3733F9F1" box="[796,867,1566,1593]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="5.[189,231,1873,1899]" captionTargetBox="[403,1215,297,1816]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[374,1244,262,1833]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Fig. 1 (continued on next page). Phylogeny of Ophion Fabricius, 1798 as obtained from cytochrome oxidase 1 (COI) sequences. Maximum likelihood tree is shown with clade support including 234 Ophion and 3 outgroup specimens is shown based on 150 bootstrap iterations using the General Time Reversible model and analysed with MEGA-X. The sample ids “NJBC” refer to the BOLD database." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3476404" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3476404/files/figure.png" pageId="59" pageNumber="60">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
) forms three separate groups that share the same distinguishing characters.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
